# Atomic Design

All UI components follow atomic design. Place components in the correct level:

```
src/components/
├── atoms/          Pure primitives. No business logic, no state, no API calls.
├── molecules/      Combine 2-3 atoms. Minimal local state (e.g., controlled input).
├── organisms/      Complex sections. May connect to Redux. May fetch data.
├── templates/      Page layouts. Slot composition via children/props. No data fetching.
```

Pages live in `src/app/` (Next.js App Router routes).

## Directory Convention

Every component in its own directory:

```
atoms/Button/
├── index.tsx
└── Button.test.tsx
```

## Classification Rules

- **Atom**: renders a single HTML element or wraps one primitive (Button, Input, Label, Icon, Badge, Spinner). Zero props that carry domain meaning.
- **Molecule**: combines 2-3 atoms into a small reusable unit (FormField, SearchBar, NavItem). May have local state for UI behavior (focus, hover). No Redux, no API calls.
- **Organism**: domain-aware section (Header, GameBoard, CourseCard, EvaluationPanel). May use `useAppSelector`, `useAppDispatch`, or RTK Query hooks.
- **Template**: pure layout (DashboardTemplate, AuthTemplate). Accepts `children` or named slots. Never fetches data.

## Rules

- Never put business logic in atoms
- Never use atoms directly in page files — compose through molecules/organisms
- Never connect atoms or molecules to Redux
- When in doubt, start at the simpler level and promote when complexity grows
- Export components as named exports from `index.tsx`
